Does Letter and Background Color Have an Effect on Reading Speed?

Introduction

Most reading we do is in a basic sans or serif font with near-black text and a near-white background. Itâs obvious that distracting colors can make it more difficult to read text, but does it significantly affect reading speed? In this study, participants were given three paragraphs of text to read, each selected from a different public domain book: Vanity Fair by William Makepeace Thackeray, Northanger Abbey by Jane Austen, and The Pickwick Papers by Charles Dickens. One paragraph was colored black and white, one was colored with rainbow text on a white background, and the third was with multicolored-text over a multicolored background.

Hypothesis

âThis study used a complete block design, where each participant was exposed to all three color conditions, controlling for individual reading speed differences.â

Model

This is the model for the study:

\[ Y_{ij} = \mu + \alpha_{i} + \beta_{j} + \varepsilon_{ij} \\ \text{or} \\ Y_{ij} = \mu + \alpha_{Participant} + \beta_{ColorCondition} + \varepsilon_{ij} \]

Where - \(Y_{ij}\): Speed in seconds for participant \(i\) under color condition \(j\) - \(\mu\): Overall intercept (grand mean) - \(\alpha_i\): Effect of the Participant (blocking effect) - \(\beta_j\): Effect of Color Condition (treatment effect) - \(\varepsilon_{ij}\): Residual error

The null hypothesis for the study is that the changing of color condition has no effect on reading speed. The alternative hypothesis for the study is that the changing of color condition has an effect on reading speed.

\[ \begin{aligned} H_0 &: \beta_j = 0 \quad \text{for all conditions} \\ H_A &: \beta_j \neq 0 \quad \text{for some j} \end{aligned} \]

Alpha

An alpha level of 0.05 was selected to reflect a conventional significance threshold, as neither Type I nor Type II errors were deemed to carry substantially greater consequences in the context of this study.

\[ \alpha = 0.05 \]

Methods

3 paragraphs were prepared using each from 3 public domain books, Vanity Fair, Northanger Abbey, and The PickWick papers. Each of these were chosen as they are public domain from somewhat similar time periods and genres. Paragraphs selected had around 276 words, and other sentences within context were selected and added to make them each exactly 276 words. Paragraphs were each set at size 15 pt in Google Docs, with a 6.5â margin. The first paragraph had black text on a white background, the second had colored text on a white background, and the third, colored text on a colored background.

Text was colored using Google Apps Script code. Values were tweaked so that color variation and contrast were sufficient enough to distinguish between the letters and the backgrounds. Code for this is pasted below. If text could end up the same color as itâs background, it would be entirely illegible, whereas if it was perfectly contrasted, readability would be near identical to the black text on a white background, so discretion was taken. Itâs noteworthy that the code outputs nearly identical alteration every time however, so reproducibility using the code is reasonable.

The paragraphs were presented to the participants in a random order. Participants indicated they had started reading, and a timer was started. When participants indicated they were finished, the timer was stopped. Results were recorded after each paragraph.

Code for colored text only

        function rainbowLetters() {
          const body = DocumentApp.getActiveDocument().getBody();
          const text = body.editAsText();
          const fullText = text.getText();
        
          for (let i = 0; i < fullText.length; i++) {
            const char = fullText.charAt(i);
            if (char !== ' ' && char !== '\n') {
              const color = getRandomDarkVibrantColor();
              text.setForegroundColor(i, i, color);
            }
          }
        }
        
        function getRandomVibrantColor() {
          // Random hue (0â360), high saturation (70â100%), dark lightness (10â40%)
          const h = Math.floor(Math.random() * 360);
          const s = Math.floor(Math.random() * 31) + 70;  // 70â100%
          const l = Math.floor(Math.random() * 31) + 20;  // 10â40% for darker tone
          return hslToHex(h, s, l);
        }
        
        function hslToHex(h, s, l) {
          s /= 100;
          l /= 100;
        
          const c = (1 - Math.abs(2 * l - 1)) * s;
          const x = c * (1 - Math.abs((h / 60) % 2 - 1));
          const m = l - c / 2;
          let r = 0, g = 0, b = 0;
        
          if (h < 60) [r, g, b] = [c, x, 0];
          else if (h < 120) [r, g, b] = [x, c, 0];
          else if (h < 180) [r, g, b] = [0, c, x];
          else if (h < 240) [r, g, b] = [0, x, c];
          else if (h < 300) [r, g, b] = [x, 0, c];
          else [r, g, b] = [c, 0, x];
        
          r = Math.round((r + m) * 255);
          g = Math.round((g + m) * 255);
          b = Math.round((b + m) * 255);
        
          return rgbToHex(r, g, b);
        }
        
        function rgbToHex(r, g, b) {
          return (
            "#" +
            [r, g, b]
              .map(x => x.toString(16).padStart(2, '0'))
              .join('')
          );
        }

Code for colored text and background

Show code 


        function rainbowLettersMixedLightness() {
          const body = DocumentApp.getActiveDocument().getBody();
          const text = body.editAsText();
          const fullText = text.getText();
        
          for (let i = 0; i < fullText.length; i++) {
            const char = fullText.charAt(i);
            if (char !== ' ' && char !== '\n') {
              // Randomly decide: light text on dark bg OR dark text on light bg
              const isLightText = Math.random() < 0.5;
        
              const textHSL = isLightText ? getRandomLightHSL() : getRandomDarkHSL();
        
              let bgHSL, contrast, attempts = 0;
        
              // Generate background color with opposite lightness
              do {
                bgHSL = isLightText ? getRandomDarkHSL() : getRandomLightHSL();
        
                const textLum = getLuminance(textHSL.h, textHSL.s, textHSL.l);
                const bgLum = getLuminance(bgHSL.h, bgHSL.s, bgHSL.l);
                contrast = getContrastRatio(textLum, bgLum);
        
                attempts++;
              } while (contrast < 2.0 && attempts < 30); // adjust 2.0 for stricter contrast
        
              const textColor = hslToHex(textHSL.h, textHSL.s, textHSL.l);
              const bgColor = hslToHex(bgHSL.h, bgHSL.s, bgHSL.l);
        
              text.setForegroundColor(i, i, textColor);
              text.setBackgroundColor(i, i, bgColor);
            }
          }
        }
        
        function getRandomLightHSL() {
          return {
            h: Math.floor(Math.random() * 360),
            s: Math.floor(Math.random() * 31) + 70, // 70â100%
            l: Math.floor(Math.random() * 21) + 80  // 80â100%
          };
        }
        
        function getRandomDarkHSL() {
          return {
            h: Math.floor(Math.random() * 360),
            s: Math.floor(Math.random() * 31) + 70, // 70â100%
            l: Math.floor(Math.random() * 31) + 10  // 10â40%
          };
        }
        
        function hslToHex(h, s, l) {
          s /= 100;
          l /= 100;
        
          const c = (1 - Math.abs(2 * l - 1)) * s;
          const x = c * (1 - Math.abs((h / 60) % 2 - 1));
          const m = l - c / 2;
        
          let r = 0, g = 0, b = 0;
        
          if (h < 60) [r, g, b] = [c, x, 0];
          else if (h < 120) [r, g, b] = [x, c, 0];
          else if (h < 180) [r, g, b] = [0, c, x];
          else if (h < 240) [r, g, b] = [0, x, c];
          else if (h < 300) [r, g, b] = [x, 0, c];
          else [r, g, b] = [c, 0, x];
        
          r = Math.round((r + m) * 255);
          g = Math.round((g + m) * 255);
          b = Math.round((b + m) * 255);
        
          return (
            "#" +
            [r, g, b]
              .map(x => x.toString(16).padStart(2, '0'))
              .join('')
          );
        }
        
        function getLuminance(h, s, l) {
          const hex = hslToHex(h, s, l);
          const r = parseInt(hex.substr(1, 2), 16) / 255;
          const g = parseInt(hex.substr(3, 2), 16) / 255;
          const b = parseInt(hex.substr(5, 2), 16) / 255;
        
          const [R, G, B] = [r, g, b].map(c =>
            c <= 0.03928 ? c / 12.92 : Math.pow((c + 0.055) / 1.055, 2.4)
          );
        
          return 0.2126 * R + 0.7152 * G + 0.0722 * B;
        }
        
        function getContrastRatio(lum1, lum2) {
          const L1 = Math.max(lum1, lum2);
          const L2 = Math.min(lum1, lum2);
          return (L1 + 0.05) / (L2 + 0.05);
        }

Assumptions

Code 
rr_aov <- aov(Seconds ~ Individual + ColorCondition, data = rr)

# Set model
model <- rr_aov  # Replace with your actual model object

# Extract residuals and fitted values
res <- residuals(model)
fit <- fitted(model)
n <- length(res)

# Residual dataframe (used in p1 and p3)
# !!! Grouping variable: Individual (Participant ID)
resid_df <- tibble(
  residuals = res,
  fitted = fit,
  order = 1:n,
  type = if ("Individual" %in% names(rr)) as.character(rr$Individual) else "All"
)

# QQ plot data
d <- tibble(
  x_sample = sort(res),
  z_theoretical = qnorm(ppoints(n))
)

# SE function for QQ bands
se_z <- function(z, n) sqrt((1 + z^2) / (2 * (n - 1)))

# QQ confidence band data
band <- tibble(
  z = seq(-2.2, 2.2, length.out = 300),
  n = n,
  sample_sd = sd(d$x_sample),
  se = sample_sd * se_z(z, n),
  line = mean(d$x_sample) + sample_sd * z,
  upper = line + 2 * se,
  lower = line - 2 * se,
  robust_sd = IQR(d$x_sample) / 1.349,
  robust_line = median(d$x_sample) + z * robust_sd,
  robust_se = robust_sd * se_z(z, n),
  robust_upper = robust_line + 2 * robust_se,
  robust_lower = robust_line - 2 * robust_se
)

Residuals vs Fitted - Constant Variance Assumption

Our variance looks good. We do have some straggling data points at the beginning and end, but this is to be expected if our passages are giving different results for the passages.

QQ Plot - Normally Distributed Residuals

The QQ plot suggests that the residuals are approximately normally distributed. Although there is a slight S-shaped curve that pushes the boundaries, all points lie close to the reference line and within the confidence bands. Therefore, we consider the normality assumption reasonably satisfied.

Residuals vs Order - Independent Residuals

There are two Residual vs Order charts, one colored by individual and one by the passage. There is interestingly enough a âsinâ up and down curve to the data, but it may just be caused by the separation in how long it took for one specific passage to be read by the participant. Itâs possible there is no pattern here. Either way, for now we will consider the requirement for independent residuals is met.

We can run our Anova.

Anova and Analysis

Code 
rr_aov <- aov(Seconds ~ Individual + ColorCondition, data = rr)
summary(rr_aov)
               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)   
Individual      3 2279.3   759.8  12.484 0.00545 **
ColorCondition  2  573.5   286.7   4.712 0.05888 . 
Residuals       6  365.2    60.9                   
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Itâs not surprising that reader is significant with a p-value of .00545. Everybody reads at different speeds. Itâs noteworthy that comprehension was not being tested, so what each participant considered as the paragraph being âreadâ is different, but regardless this is not surprising. It is helpful to know, however, that a significant portion of unexplained variation was reduced by blocking the individuals, so our test is more accurate for Color Condition.

Color Condition was quite nearly significant with a rounded p-value of .059. lthough it appeared somewhat comparable to the other texts in legibility, the data suggest a possible reduction in readability under this condition. With only 4 individuals tested, itâs quite possible that the results of the test could go either way with more evidence and perhaps more tightly controlled timing and standardized testing for reading comprehension to set baseline for what criteria text could be read under.

Contrasts

Letâs run some contrasts to see if the colored text with white background is different from the colored text with a colored background. We will use Dunnetâs test to compare the âCWâ or colored on white against the âCCâ or colored on colored against the basic test paragraph to see if either is significantly different.

Code 
emm <- emmeans(rr_aov, "ColorCondition")

# Compare each level to the control (level 0)
contrast(emm, method = "trt.vs.ctrl", ref = 1)  # if level 0 is the first level
 contrast estimate   SE df t.ratio p.value
 CW - BW      1.25 5.52  6   0.227  0.9544
 CC - BW     15.25 5.52  6   2.764  0.0596

Results are averaged over the levels of: Individual 
P value adjustment: dunnettx method for 2 tests

We can see that we do not have sufficient evidence to conclude that the colored over white passage is different from normal text, but we almost have sufficient evidence for the colored on colored. Itâs nearly as close as our anova p-value for Color Condition. This would suggest that itâs not just the colored text, but also the addition of the second changing and contrasting factor, the background.

Conclusion

Itâs not surprising that colors can be distracting and affect readability, but what is surprising is that this particular test is bordering the line of statistical significance. Further data collection with a larger and more diverse sample would help confirm whether the observed near-significant effect of colored backgrounds on reading speed reflects a true underlying difference.â

So does letter and background color have an effect on reading speed? Itâs a strong maybe.
